social_posts.post_text: Just got back from a quick fun ice climbing season opener to Southwestern Colorado with legends Bruce Miller and Brian McMahon.  Maybe better than the climbing itself were all the stories and games of advanced “would you rather” on the long drives between climbs. Thanks for letting me invite myself boys, and let’s do it again!!! Oh and for those who care which routes pictured here: Bridalveil Falls and the Talisman in incredibly fun shape! @arcteryx @scarpana @camp_usa #brucemiller @mag_mcmahon

The Michigan Ice Fest is really something else. Climbing above Lake Superior, teaching folks how to ice climb, getting lost on snow mobiles, and unreal local hospitality are just a few of the things I love about this one of a kind event. This year over 1400 people participated in clinics, back country experiences, and evening festivities, making for an awesome five days with some of my favorite people. 

Besides the event side of the ice festival, I’ve been asked what the allure is of climbing in Michigan. The moment you rappel onto a shelf of ice with waves crashing all around you, and pull your ropes, you immediately get it why it’s so special. This year I took @quentinclimbing to my favorite cliff where we had put up a handful of first ascents to which he added another real gem and the hardest of the lot to date, “The Lion Queen”. Without anywhere to belay he went for it without one, making for what I would assume to be probably the hardest climb in the area, and put up solo after a top rope inspection. 

Thanks @michiganicefest and @arcteryx for sending me out again this year, it was a real pleasure!

Seven days locked away in the Selkirk Mountains with endless powder and 14 of my new best friends.

✨Absolute Magic ✨
 🙏🙏🙏

The last few months have been absolutely crazy getting ready to leave for 6 weeks to try and free climb Trango (Nameless) Tower with @mattsegal and @cannonjtc.  Each day I woke up at sunrise out of a hypoxic tent, to grind out as many pitches as possible to be at work around noon, only to catch another workout before dinner. Huge shout out to the many partners who supported to make that happen @tylerjallen @james_lucas @wademorris12 @maurybirdwell @nrgreen3 and many more - I’m sorry I know you would have rather started latter in the day 🙏 and I owe you one - just ask! 

Tomorrow morning we walk into the mountains to start this mega adventure and I couldn’t be more amped! Cowboy Direct - let’s go!

🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏🙏
@arcteryx @scarpana @camp_usa @lyofood @goalzero @corosglobal @zealoptics

Cowboy Direct, 5.13a, Grade 7, Second ascent, Trango Tower, Balturo Glacier, Gilgit, Pakistan.

July 4 - August 13, 2023.

WE ARE HOME!!!

It has been an absolute pleasure the last 6 weeks traveling through Pakistan, visiting the Karakoram for the first time, and climbing the second ascent of the Cowboy Direct with @mattsegal and @cannonjtc . This trip was my fourth trip to a greater Himalayan range, which had me with low expectations of “success” but fired up for a grand adventure with these gentlemen regardless of an outcome. 

Matt and I, (think Shrek and Donkey), have climbed a ton together over the years, but I was hesitant to commit to try and free climb Trango Tower.  It was was an obvious objective for our partnership, but we knew we couldn’t pull it off just the two of us.  We were ecstatic when Jordan Cannon, with his granite wizardry, extensive wall experience, and most importantly his psych for adventure, accepted our offer to join us for his first expedition to the Himalaya.

Matt did an incredible job coordinating with our outfitter @pakistan_higher_ground arranging ALL of the logistics 🙏 and coordinated with the two previous North Face expeditions to the area, ensuring we had all the right equipment and the right beta to keep from getting sick in basecamp.  Jordan meticulously prepared our climbing gear so that we could stay organized on the wall and could efficiently haul (I can honestly say I learned a ton from him here) the many hundreds of pounds we needed high on the mountain.  I organized our alpine gear, wall food, sleeping systems (major shout out to @grade7equipment and the POD tech), and promised to keep Jordan alive 😘 as he had almost no experience in crampons prior to the trip.

**************
Continued in comments 
**************

The Arc’teryx Academy is in full swing. One of my favorite weeks of the entire year, seeing so many amazing friends, seeing some great presentations,  eating some epic sushi, listening to some all time music, giving some climbing clinics, and even a day or two to  get out and climb some of the areas best  steep cracks. Excited to watch the film about Yamnuska tonight and to dance the night away with some of my best friends and the Arc crew. ✌️ 🌄🌅 @arcteryx @arcteryxacademy

👀LOOK CLOSER!👀

Can anyone name the mountain(s) in these slides!? I zoomed in on this photo from our portaledge bivy high on Trango Tower and was like “oh snap there it is!”

#karakorum #pakistan #k2

Halfway through pitch 15 of the Cowboy Direct the crack just peters out and ends in a blank granite wall. Luckily there are just enough edges and sloping foot holds to make a super delicate traverse left into another crack system that goes all the way to the summit.

It was a pretty stressful spot on the wall for a lot of reasons but one of them was that this pitch was often soaked at the beginning (a delicate 5.12 flare) and at the end (the 13- crux which was a major woof.) Here @cannonjtc gets ready to make the traverse out of the corner left into the final crux traverse which he styled first go like an absolute boss on the first day it was dry enough, warm enough, and we were acclimated enough to give it a go on lead.

On another note, it’s been a month now since getting off the wall and I can finally feel my toes 100% again which has me starting to want to climb again, right in time for fall temps back home. It feels good to feel the 🔥 again to start training and rebuilding all the lost muscle and strength from so much time at altitude with little food!

@mattsegal @arcteryx @scarpana @camp_usa @lyofood @goalzero
#trangotowers #pakistan #boosticsforthewin

Three boys and an American dream. 
Scarpa athletes Jordan Cannon and Jesse Huey with Matt Segal, went to Pakistan for six weeks to try to repeat the Cowboy Direct route, last climbed on 7 September 1995.
